import kotlin.test.assertEquals

class CommissionTest {

    @Test
    fun testCommissionWithValidAmount() {
        // Arrange
        val expectedCommission = "50.0 руб. - комиссия с \"Visa\""

        // Act
        val actualCommission = commission()

        // Assert
        assertEquals(expectedCommission, actualCommission)
    }

    @Test
    fun testCommissionWithInvalidAmount() {
        // Arrange
        val expectedCommission = "Неправильная сумма."

        // Act
        val actualCommission = commission()

        // Assert
        assertEquals(expectedCommission, actualCommission)
    }
}
```

In this example, we have two test cases: `testCommissionWithValidAmount` and `testCommissionWithInvalidAmount`. 

In the `testCommissionWithValidAmount` test case, we set up the expected commission value based on the provided valid amount. We then call the `commission()` function and store the actual commission value. Finally, we use the `assertEquals` function from the testing framework to compare the expected and actual commission values.

Similarly, in the `testCommissionWithInvalidAmount` test case, we set up the expected commission value based on the provided invalid amount. We call the `commission()` function and store the actual commission value. Finally, we use the `assertEquals` function to compare the expected and actual commission values.

You can add more test cases to cover different scenarios and edge cases. Make sure to import the necessary dependencies for the testing framework you are using.

